where ΔG is the Gibbs free energy. For electrolysis of water ΔG=237 kJ/mol (Gabriele and Paolo, 2012). TΔS is the thermal energy requirement.

Faraday’s law is used in the modelling; it relates the electrical energy needed to split water to the chemical conversion rate in molar quantities. The electrode kinetics can be expressed using empirical current-voltage (I-U) relationships. The basic form of the I-U curve has been discussed in (Đukić and Firak, 2011; Gabriele and Paolo, 2012), and the voltage (U) for a given temperature can be defined as
(8)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
